declarations.comments:
The `Arbitrary` class represents those types whose values can be
_randomly-generated_.

`arbitrary` uses the `Gen` monad to express a random generator for
the type `t`. Combinators in the `Test.StrongCheck.Gen`
module can be used to construct random generators.
declarations.title: Arbitrary

declarations.comments:
The `Coarbitrary` class represents types which appear on the left of
an `Arbitrary` function arrow.

To construct an `Arbitrary` instance for the type `a -> b`, we need to
use the input of type `a` to _perturb_ a random generator for `b`. This
is the role of the `coarbitrary` function.

`Coarbitrary` instances can be written using the `perturbGen` function.
declarations.title: Coarbitrary

declarations.comments:
A seed for the linear congruential generator. We omit a `Semiring`
instance because there is no `zero` value, as 0 is not an acceptable
seed for the generator.
declarations.title: Seed

declarations.comments: The result of a property test.
declarations.title: Result

declarations.comments: A class for types that can be treated as a property test result.
declarations.title: Testable

declarations.comments: Checks the proposition for 100 random values.
declarations.title: quickCheck

declarations.comments: Checks the proposition for the specified number of random values.
declarations.title: quickCheck'

declarations.comments: Checks the proposition for the specified number of random values, starting with a specific seed.
declarations.title: quickCheckWithSeed

declarations.comments:
Checks the proposition for the specified number of random values in a pure
setting, returning an array of results.
declarations.title: quickCheckPure

declarations.comments:
Exhaustively checks the proposition for all possible values. Assumes the
generator is a finite generator.
declarations.title: smallCheck

declarations.comments:
Exhaustively checks the proposition for all possible values in a pure
setting, returning an array of results. Assumes the generator is a finite
generator.
declarations.title: smallCheckPure

declarations.comments:
Checks that the proposition has a certain probability of being true for
arbitrary values.
declarations.title: statCheck

declarations.comments:
Checks that the proposition has a certain probability of being true for
arbitrary values in a pure setting, returning a result.
declarations.title: statCheckPure

declarations.comments: Checks that the specified proposition holds. Useful for unit tests.
declarations.title: assert

declarations.comments:
Asserts that two values are equal, resulting in a `Failure` if they are
not, with a message showing the values involved.
declarations.title: assertEq

declarations.comments:
Asserts that two values are not equal, resulting in a `Failure` if they
are, with a message showing the values involved.
declarations.title: assertNotEq

declarations.comments:
Converts a `Boolean` into a `Result` by lifting a message into `Failed`
when the boolean is `false`.
declarations.title: annotate

declarations.comments:
The `Arbitrary` class represents those types whose values can be
_randomly-generated_.

`arbitrary` uses the `Gen` monad to express a random generator for
the type `t`. Combinators in the `Test.StrongCheck.Gen`
module can be used to construct random generators.
declarations.title: Arbitrary

declarations.comments:
The `Coarbitrary` class represents types which appear on the left of
an `Arbitrary` function arrow.

To construct an `Arbitrary` instance for the type `a -> b`, we need to
use the input of type `a` to _perturb_ a random generator for `b`. This
is the role of the `coarbitrary` function.

`Coarbitrary` instances can be written using the `perturbGen` function.
declarations.title: Coarbitrary

declarations.comments:
A newtype for `Number` whose `Eq` instance uses an epsilon value to allow
for precision erros when comparing.
declarations.title: ApproxNumber

declarations.comments:
A deterministic generator that produces values from the specified array,
in sequence.
declarations.title: allInArray

declarations.comments:
A deterministic generator that produces integers from the specified
inclusive range, in sequence.
declarations.title: allInRange

declarations.comments:
Applies a state to a generator to possibly produce the next state,
a value, and the next generator.
declarations.title: applyGen

declarations.comments: Creates a generator of elements ranging from 0 to the maximum size.
declarations.title: arrayOf

declarations.comments: Creates a generator of elements ranging from 1 to the maximum size.
declarations.title: arrayOf1

declarations.comments: A generator for characters.
declarations.title: charGen

declarations.comments:
Creates a generator that generates real numbers between the specified
inclusive range.
declarations.title: choose

declarations.comments:
Creates a generator that generates integers between the specified
inclusive range.
declarations.title: chooseInt

declarations.comments:
Creates a generator that produces chunks of values in the specified size.
Will extend the generator if necessary to produce a chunk of the specified
size, but will not turn a finite generator into an infinite generator.
declarations.title: chunked

declarations.comments:
Drains a finite generator of all values. Or blows up if you called it on
an infinite generator.
declarations.title: collectAll

declarations.comments:
Drops a certain number of values from the generator. May produce
an empty generator if called on a finite generator.
declarations.title: dropGen

declarations.comments: Creates a generator that chooses an element from among a set of elements.
declarations.title: elements

declarations.comments:
Extends a generator to produce *at least* the specified number of values.
Will not turn a finite generator into an infinite one.
declarations.title: extend

declarations.comments:
Folds over a generator to produce a value. Either the generator or the
user-defined function may halt the fold.
declarations.title: foldGen

declarations.comments:
Folds over a generator to produce a value. Either the generator or the
user-defined function may halt the fold. Returns not just the value
created through folding, but also the successor generator.
declarations.title: foldGen'

declarations.comments: Generates elements by the specified frequencies (which will be normalized).
declarations.title: frequency

declarations.comments:
Ensures that a given generator can produce an infinite number of values,
assuming it can produce at least one.
declarations.title: infinite

declarations.comments: Fairly interleaves two generators.
declarations.title: interleave

declarations.comments:
A deterministic generator that produces all possible combinations of
choosing exactly k elements from the specified array.
declarations.title: nChooseK

declarations.comments:
Creates a generator that chooses another generator from the specified list
at random, and then generates a value with that generator.
declarations.title: oneOf

declarations.comments:
A deterministic generator that produces all possible permutations of
the specified array.
declarations.title: perms

declarations.comments:
Creates a function generator that will always generate the same output
for the same input.
declarations.title: repeatable

declarations.comments:
Resizes the generator so the size parameter passed into the generator
will be equal to the specified size.
declarations.title: resize

declarations.comments:
Runs a generator to produce a specified number of values, returning both
an array containing the values and the successor Gen that can be used to
continue the generation process at a later time.
declarations.title: runGen

declarations.comments:
Samples a generator, producing the specified number of values. Uses
default settings for the initial generator state.
declarations.title: sample

declarations.comments: Samples a generator, producing the specified number of values.
declarations.title: sample'

declarations.comments: Shows a sample of values generated from the specified generator.
declarations.title: showSample

declarations.comments: Shows a sample of values generated from the specified generator.
declarations.title: showSample'

declarations.comments: Same as shuffle' but with default for the chunk size.
declarations.title: shuffle

declarations.comments:
Creates a generator that mixes up the order of the specified generator.
This is achieved by chunking the generator with the specified size
and then shuffling each chunk before continuing to the next.
declarations.title: shuffle'

declarations.comments: Creates a generator that produces shuffled versions of the provided array.
declarations.title: shuffleArray

declarations.comments: Creates a generator that depends on the size parameter.
declarations.title: sized

declarations.comments: Creates a generator that depends on access to the generator state.
declarations.title: stateful

declarations.comments:
Filters a generator to produce only values satisfying the specified
predicate.
declarations.title: suchThat

declarations.comments:
Tries to filter a generator such that it only produces values satisfying
the specified predicate.
declarations.title: suchThatMaybe

declarations.comments:
Takes the first number of values from the generator. Will turn an infinite
generator into a finite generator.
declarations.title: takeGen

declarations.comments:
Converts the generator into a function that, given the initial state,
returns a lazy list.
declarations.title: toLazyList

declarations.comments:
Transforms one gen into another, passing along user-supplied state.
Either the generator being transformed or the transforming function may
halt the transformation.
declarations.title: transGen

declarations.comments: Fixes a generator on a certain variant, given by the specified seed.
declarations.title: variant

declarations.comments: Creates a generator that generates arrays of some specified size.
declarations.title: vectorOf

declarations.comments: Wraps an effect in a generator that ignores the input state.
declarations.title: wrapEffect

declarations.comments:
A seed for the linear congruential generator. We omit a `Semiring`
instance because there is no `zero` value, as 0 is not an acceptable
seed for the generator.
declarations.title: Seed

declarations.comments: The *multiplier*: a magic constant for the linear congruential generator
declarations.title: lcgM

declarations.comments: The *increment*: a magic constant for the linear congruential generator
declarations.title: lcgC

declarations.comments:
The *modulus*: a magic constant for the linear congruential generator.
It is equal to 2^31 - 1, a Mersenne prime. It is useful for this value to
be prime, because then the requirement of the initial seed being coprime
to the modulus is satisfied when the seed is between 1 and lcgN - 1.
declarations.title: lcgN

declarations.comments: Step the linear congruential generator
declarations.title: lcgNext

declarations.comments: Perturb a seed value
declarations.title: lcgPerturb

declarations.comments: Create a random seed
declarations.title: randomSeed

declarations.comments:
Creates a landscape whose initial points are randomly chosen across
the entire landscape, using the default GenState and Decay.
declarations.title: everywhere

declarations.comments:
Creates a landscape whose initial points are randomly chosen across
the entire landscape.
declarations.title: everywhere'

declarations.comments: Moves to a location in a landscape that was previously sampled.
declarations.title: moveTo

declarations.comments:
Creates a landscape that samples the area around a location, using the
default GenState and Decay.
declarations.title: nearby

declarations.comments: Creates a landscape that samples the area around a location.
declarations.title: nearby'

declarations.comments: Samples around the current location area, returning just the values.
declarations.title: sampleHere

declarations.comments: Samples around the current location area, returning full state information.
declarations.title: sampleHere'

declarations.comments:
Picks somewhere and forms a landscape around that location, using the
default GenState and Decay.
declarations.title: somewhere

declarations.comments: Picks somewhere and forms a landscape around that location.
declarations.title: somewhere'

declarations.comments:
The class for things which can be perturbed.

Laws:
  forall a, 0 >= n <= 1:
  ((>=) n) <<< dist a <$> (perturb n a) must be an infinite generator of `true` values.
declarations.title: Perturb

declarations.comments: Combines two perturbers to produce a perturber of the product
declarations.title: perturberProduct

declarations.comments: Combines two perturbers to produce a perturber of the sum
declarations.title: perturberSum

declarations.comments: Creates a perturber for numbers that fall within the specified range.
declarations.title: bounded

declarations.comments: Creates a perturber for integers that fall within the specified range.
declarations.title: boundedInt

declarations.comments: Creates a perturber that perturbs nothing.
declarations.title: nonPerturber

declarations.comments:
Given one example, searches for other examples that satisfy a provided
boolean predicate.

The search operates out-to-in, in an attempt to find examples that are
as far removed from the provided example as possible. The sampling size
parameter determines how many samples to take at every level of
searching, while the attempts parameter determines how many levels.
declarations.title: searchIn'

declarations.comments:
The same as search', but uses defaults for attempt count and sample size.
Will search a total of 10,000 examples before giving up.
declarations.title: searchIn
